</description><pubDate>Thu, 17 Oct 2013 02:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">http://nwazet.com:80/pi-microsd-adapter</guid></item><item><title>Mini USB WiFi (802.11b/g/n)</title><link>http://nwazet.com:80/mini-usb-wifi</link><description>&lt;p&gt;When there is no nearby Ethernet connection, you'll need a USB wifi adapter to connect your Raspberry Pi to the Internet or to your local network. This very small adapter will barely stick out, and will be recognized by all our Linux distributions without the need to install any new drivers. We picked this adapter for those cases where a compact project is more important than range. For better range, we recommend &lt;a href="/usb-wifi"&gt;our larger USB WiFi adapter&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Raspbian Configuration&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To use this WiFi module with the Raspbian distribution on the Raspberry Pi, please follow these steps:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From the console, as root (or using sudo), edit the network interfaces configuration file.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;
nano /etc/network/interfaces
&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Edit the file to include a wlan0 interface with the SSID and pre-shared key of the network you want to join.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;
auto lo

iface lo inet loopback
iface eth0 inet dhcp

allow-hotplug wlan0
auto wlan0
iface wlan0 inet dhcp
wpa-ssid "YourSSID"
wpa-psk "YourKey"
&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Reboot the Raspberry Pi after saving the updated configuration file.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Specifications&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;USB 2.0/1.1&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;WiFi IEEE 802.11b/g/n (2.4GHz)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Sticks out only 8mm from the USB port&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Data Rate: 1Mbps to 150Mbps down and up&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Realtek RTl8192cu Chipset&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Dimensions: 19 x 14.3 x 6.2mm&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Weight: 2.2g&lt;/li&gt;
